Explore amplicon data with phyoseq

We are starting from a previosly produced phyloseq object to explore our amplicon data. To browse more functionalities than covered in the tutorial, please visit the phyloseq website https://joey711.github.io/phyloseq/

0. Load required libraries

To run this tutorial you need to have the libraries phyloseq and ggplot2 installed. We now load both libraries into R.

library(phyloseq)
library(ggplot2)

# This command sets the ggplot theme to black and white
theme_set(theme_bw())

1. Import phyloseq object

Now we import a previously created phyloseq object. If you don’t have a phyloseq object, check out the documentation at https://joey711.github.io/phyloseq/import-data.html for help to create one from your data.

my_physeq<-readRDS("phyloseq.rds")
my_physeq
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 218 taxa and 20 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 20 samples by 3 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 218 taxa by 8 taxonomic ranks ]
## phy_tree()    Phylogenetic Tree: [ 218 tips and 216 internal nodes ]

2. Get basic stats

Before analysis it is always crucial to sanity-check your dataset. Are all expected samples there? Do my metadata look as expected. In this case we check the number of taxa (OTUs/ASVs), number of samples, metadata, and library size (sample sums) in your phyloseq object.

# number of taxa
ntaxa(my_physeq)
## [1] 218
# number of samples
nsamples(my_physeq)
## [1] 20
# check metadata
head(sample_data(my_physeq))

# check and plot library size (count sums)
my_sums<-as.data.frame(sample_sums(my_physeq), optional=FALSE, col.names=c("1"))
colnames(my_sums)<-"sample_sums"
ggplot(my_sums, aes(x=row.names(my_sums),y=sample_sums)) + 
  geom_point() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust=1)
  )

3. Plot alpha diversity

We start our data exploration by plotting alpha diversity metrics. Phyloseq has a range of metrics to choose from and it depends on your question and dataset which of the metrics you want to know. For these metrics you should always use the raw counts and NOT relative abundances. One thing that is influencing alpha diversity estimates is library size. We saw in the initial data exploration that library size (sample sums) differed quite a lot for some of the samples. To have the datasets more comparable we can rarefy the data, meaning we reduce the sample sums to the count of the sample with the lowest count. If your data contain some samples with very low counts, this is not always advisable as you will loose a lot of information. In this case however, most samples are in a similar range, and we have only a few higher outliers, so we decide to rarefy.

# rarefy 
my_physeq_rare <- rarefy_even_depth(my_physeq, sample.size = min(sample_sums(my_physeq)), rngseed = 19)
## `set.seed(19)` was used to initialize repeatable random subsampling.
## Please record this for your records so others can reproduce.
## Try `set.seed(19); .Random.seed` for the full vector
## ...
## 8OTUs were removed because they are no longer 
## present in any sample after random subsampling
## ...
my_physeq_rare
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 210 taxa and 20 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 20 samples by 3 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 210 taxa by 8 taxonomic ranks ]
## phy_tree()    Phylogenetic Tree: [ 210 tips and 208 internal nodes ]
# check rareficatiob effect on library size 
my_rsums<-as.data.frame(sample_sums(my_physeq_rare), optional=FALSE, col.names=c("1"))
colnames(my_rsums)<-"sample_sums"
ggplot(my_rsums, aes(x=row.names(my_rsums),y=sample_sums)) + 
  geom_point() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust=1)
  )

We fist plot an overview of 4 alpha diversity measures and color the data by our metadata category ‘Time’. Note: We receive a warning that there are no signletons in the data. This is not automatically a problem but it is important to pay attention to these warnings to make sure, the data haven’t been filtered or otherwise pre-processed.

# plot multiple alpha diversity measures and color by metadata
my_alpha <- plot_richness(my_physeq_rare, 
                          measures = c("Observed", "Chao1", "Shannon", "Simpson"), 
                          color="Time") 
my_alpha

The great thing about the plots created by phyloseq, is that they are customizable as normal ggplot objects. So you can easily adjust these plots according to your need. For example we can now add a title and caption to the plot.

# customize plot using ggplot features
my_alpha + 
  ggtitle("Alpha diversity - overview") + 
  labs(caption = "alpha diversity calculated on unfiltered data (only OTUs with 0 counts in all samples were removed)")

Especially, when having a lot of samples, we might want to compare the alpha diversity between groups of samples. For example here we group by ‘Time’ groups and ‘Mock’ dataset.

# group samples
my_alpha2 <- plot_richness(my_physeq_rare, 
                           measures = c("Observed"), 
                           x="Time", 
                           color = "Time") 
my_alpha2

And again we can add additional ggplot layers, such as a violon plot.

# add ggplot layers
my_alpha2 + 
  geom_violin(fill=NA)

4. Plot taxonomic profiles

To plot the taxonomic profiles, we can transform the counts into relative abundances. It is possible to do additional filtering to remove los abundant taxa, certain samples, or to just keep the top taxa. Information on how to do this can be found here https://joey711.github.io/phyloseq/preprocess.html

# transform counts to relative abundances
my_physeq_rel <- transform_sample_counts(my_physeq, function(OTU) OTU / sum(OTU))

To produce stacked bar charts, we need to choose the taxonomic level that we are interested in and agglomerate the OTUs belonging to the sampe taxon.

Stacked bar chart at Phylum level:

# agglomerate at Phylum level
my_phyla <- tax_glom(my_physeq_rel,taxrank = "Phylum")

# stacked bar plot for Phyla 
my_bar_phyla <- plot_bar(my_phyla, fill="Phylum") + 
  scale_fill_discrete(na.value="grey90") + 
  ggtitle("Relative abundances at Phylum level") 
my_bar_phyla

Stacked bar chart at Class level:

# agglomerate at Class level
my_class <- tax_glom(my_physeq_rel,taxrank = "Class")

# stacked bar plot for Class 
my_bar_class <- plot_bar(my_class, fill="Class") + 
  scale_fill_discrete(na.value="grey90") + 
  ggtitle("Relative abundances at Class level") 
my_bar_class

Another way to plot the relative abundances, can be bubble plots. These are useful, if you want to add more information. Also, it might be easier to separate more taxa in one plot, as a bar plot with too many colors get hard to read. To create a bubble plot we have to tweak phyloseq a little bit, as this plot is not implemented by default.

We first agglomerate data at Genus level and then create a bar plot object

my_genera = tax_glom(my_physeq_rel, "Genus")
my_bar_gen <- plot_bar(my_genera)

Then we have to remove the plot layer itself (since we don’t want a stacked bar chart kind of plot).

my_bar_gen$layers <- my_bar_gen$layers[-1]

Now we need to add our plot layer using ggplot2. First, we will save a variable maxC that contains the maximum relative abundace for a single genus to help us create an appropriate size legend in the plot. Then, we create and customize the actual plot itself. Even though we are showing the genuses we can add extra information as color (or shape). In this case we color by phylum and can therefore clearly see that most detenced Genera belong to the Firmicutes Phylum. Finally, we split the plot into separate facets by metadata category.

# sets maximum relative abundance for figure legend dimensions
maxC<-max(otu_table(my_genera)) 

# replace with bubble plot instead of bars
my_bubble_gen <- my_bar_gen + 
    geom_point(aes_string(x="Sample", y="Genus", size="Abundance", color = "Phylum"), alpha = 0.7) +
    scale_size_continuous(limits = c(0.001,maxC)) +
    xlab("Sample") +
    ylab("Genus") +
    ggtitle("Relative abundances at Genus level") + 
    labs(caption = "Abundances below 0.001 were considered absent")

my_bubble_gen +
  facet_grid(. ~ Time, scales = "free_x", space="free")
## Warning: Removed 646 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

5. Plot beta diversity

To visualize how dimilar or dissimilar the taxonomic composition is between samples, we can do an ordination. Phyloseq offers a range of ditance metrics and ordination methods and it depends on your data which one is the most appropriate to use. Here we will use an MDS/PCoA ordination on Bray-Curtis dissimilarities. For other options see instructions here https://joey711.github.io/phyloseq/plot_ordination-examples.html

We first create the ordination, then plot the ordination and finally customize tyhe plot by insreasing symbol size.

my_ordi <- ordinate(my_physeq_rel, 
                    method="MDS", 
                    distance="bray")
my_pcoa <- plot_ordination(my_physeq_rel, 
                           my_ordi, 
                           color="Time")

my_pcoa + 
  geom_point(size=3)

We can see in the above ordination plot that the Mock sample is driving a lot of the separation. But the Mock dataset is more of a control and we are not actually interested in this sample. We want to know the differece between time points. In this case we can remove the Mock sample and just look at the data that we want to compare.

To do that we use the prune_samples() function from phyloseq. We can now check the phyloseq object and see that instead of 20 samples we have only 19 as expected.

# remove Mock sample
my_noMock <- prune_samples(sample_names(my_physeq_rel)!="Mock",my_physeq_rel)
my_noMock
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 218 taxa and 19 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 19 samples by 3 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 218 taxa by 8 taxonomic ranks ]
## phy_tree()    Phylogenetic Tree: [ 218 tips and 216 internal nodes ]

Now we plot the ordination again without the Mock sample. We can nicely see the left-to-right separation between time points.

my_ordi2 <- ordinate(my_noMock, 
                     method="MDS", 
                     distance="bray")
my_pcoa2<- plot_ordination(my_noMock, 
                           my_ordi2, 
                           color="Time")

my_pcoa2 + 
  geom_point(size=3)
